The charts above show Peabody’s mean and median gender pay gap in pounds 
and percentages. As you can see, Peabody is unusual in that it has a negative 
gender pay gap (median -7.1%; mean -2.4%), meaning that on average - across our 
organisation – women are paid more than men.  When looking at the mean figure, 
women are paid an average of £1.20 more per hour than men and the median 
shows an average of £0.49 more per hour.  

Percentage of male and female employees in each pay band 
One reason for this is that women are well represented throughout Peabody’s three 
highest pay bands, making up 53% of the workforce at this level. At the same time, 
we also have a high number of lower paid male employees in our estates 
management service, so men make up 74% of our lowest pay band. 

